Question: How to read/write a 2d char array through a Socket?: :So I am writing a game of LAN tic-tac-toe. I have the "board" stored as a 2 dimensional char array. I want to be able to send and receive this array through Sockets. I am currently using a InputStream and OutputStream to send single bytes. However, I don't think this will work for sending the array. Also, these streams only seem capable of sending int type data. Can someone please explain to me how too send 2 dimensional char arrays over sockets using I/O streams. Example code would be great! Thanks. Current Code:public void communicate() {    try {        OutputStream os = client.getOutputStream();        InputStream is = client.getInputStream();    }    while (gameOver == false) {        char[][] board = new char[3][3];        try {            os.write(board); //this dosen't work, only sends non-array int types.         } catch (IOException e) {            e.printStackTrace();        }    }}
Please using this api: InputStream.read.
Answer:<<<api>>>: InputStream.read
<<<code>>>: 
InputStream is = client.getInputStream();
byte[] buffer = new byte[1024];
int bytesRead;
while ((bytesRead = is.read(buffer)) != -1) {
    char[][] board = new char[3][3];
    for (int i = 0; i < bytesRead; i++) {
        board[i/3][i%3] = (char) buffer[i];
    }
    // process the board
}
<<<explanation>>>: The read() method of the InputStream class reads the next byte of data from the input stream. The value byte is returned as an int in the range 0 to 255. If no byte is available because the end of the stream has been reached, the value -1 is returned.
Question: How to read/write a 2D char array through a Socket?
Please using this api: ObjectOutputStream.writeObject.
Answer:<<<api>>>: ObjectOutputStream.writeObject
<<<code>>>: 
ObjectOutputStream oos = new ObjectOutputStream(client.getOutputStream());
char[][] board = new char[3][3];
oos.writeObject(board);
<<<explanation>>>: The writeObject() method of the ObjectOutputStream class writes an object to the output stream. The object is written in a way that can be read back in using an ObjectInputStream.
```

Please note that the above code examples are for Java 8 and later. In Java 7, you would need to use a library like Google's Protocol Buffers or Apache Avro to serialize and deserialize your 2D char array.

Also, remember that you need to handle exceptions properly in your code. The above examples do not include exception handling for simplicity.

Lastly, the size of the 2D array should be known before sending it. If the size is not known beforehand, you would need to send some additional information (like the dimensions of the array) before sending the array itself.

